I agree that this would require a lot of tuning.<br>
<br>
Raiding is already encouraged by loot. However, at lower levels, inflation has made lower level loot pretty trivial. <br>
<br>
With something like this in place, there's an incentive for all players to participate in those encounters to maximize their character's potential.<br>
<br>
I'm not surprised that some people would be opposed to this. It hurts soloers a lot, relatively speaking. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uraticus7th.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Raticus 7th</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/22/02 3:42:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=22978.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: &quot;Epic experience&quot; - alternate advancement idea</span><hr size=1> &quot;Plus it'd be incentive for people to go back and farm the lower wussy Boss mobs so they                       can get that boss xp increase if they are unable to do the bigger bosses. Thus taking                       content away from the newbies.&quot;<br>
<br>
This is true in the short term. People would do this until their epic level caught up. Remember, though, you don't get any boss experience if they're rated lower than you. It's not like people could farm crush to get up to epic level 100. (or even anything above 20)<br>
<br>
I also put in the point about &quot;advancement being relatively fast&quot; to guard against that. If someone was getting solo experience on a boss mob, they would catch up to that mob's difficulty rating very quickly.<br>
<br>
The lower levels could take less experience than the upper levels. So, if you were raid level 0, and you went and killed a raid level 60, you'd pop up to raid level 40 after one kill (or something like that).<br>
<br>
